          <para id="id74989">We often think about friction in a negative way but very often friction is useful without us realizing it. If there was no friction and you tried to prop a ladder up against a wall, it would simply slide to the ground. Rock climbers use friction to maintain their grip on cliffs. The brakes of cars would be useless if it wasn't for friction!</para>
<exercise id="secfhsst_id4063"><title> Coefficients of friction </title>
          <problem id="probfhsst_id4064">
          <para id="id75008">A block of wood weighing 32 N is placed on a rough, flat inclline and a rope is tied to it. The tension in the rope can be increased to 8 N before the block starts to slide. A force of 4 N will keep the block moving at constant speed once it has been set in motion. Determine the coefficients of static and kinetic friction. </para>
          </problem>
          <solution id="solfhsst_id4067"> <list id="listfhsst_id4067" list-type="enumerated" number-style="arabic" class="stepwise">
          <item> <label> Analyse the question and determine what is asked </label>
          <para id="id75035">The weight of the block is given (32 N) and two situations are identified: One where the block is not moving (applied force is 8 N), and one where the block is moving (applied force is 4 N).</para>
          <para id="id75040">We are asked to find the coefficient for static friction <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mi>s</m:mi></m:msub></m:math> and kinetic friction <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:msub><m:mi>μ</m:mi><m:mi>k</m:mi></m:msub></m:math>.</para>
          </item> <item> <label> Find the coefficient of static friction </label>
          <equation id="id75081">
            <m:math overflow="scroll" mode="display">
              <m:mtable displaystyle="true">
                <m:mtr>
                  <m:mtd columnalign="right">
