          </m:math>
        </equation>
        <para id="id78440">As you can see, these forces are very small.</para>
        <para id="id78444">Now consider the gravitational force between the Earth and the Moon. The mass of the Earth is <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mn>5</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mn>98</m:mn><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mn>10</m:mn><m:mn>24</m:mn></m:msup></m:mrow></m:math> kg, the mass of the Moon is <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mn>7</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mn>35</m:mn><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mn>10</m:mn><m:mn>22</m:mn></m:msup></m:mrow></m:math> kg and the Earth and Moon are <m:math overflow="scroll"><m:mrow><m:mn>3</m:mn><m:mo>,</m:mo><m:mn>8</m:mn><m:mo>×</m:mo><m:msup><m:mn>10</m:mn><m:mn>8</m:mn></m:msup></m:mrow></m:math> m apart. The gravitational force between the Earth and Moon is:</para>
        <equation id="id78522">
          <m:math overflow="scroll" mode="display">
            <m:mtable displaystyle="true">
              <m:mtr>
                <m:mtd columnalign="right">
                  <m:mi>F</m:mi>
                </m:mtd>
                <m:mtd>
                  <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                </m:mtd>
                <m:mtd columnalign="left">
                  <m:mrow>
                    <m:mi>G</m:mi>
                    <m:mfrac>
                      <m:mrow>
                        <m:msub>
                          <m:mi>m</m:mi>
                          <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                        </m:msub>
                        <m:msub>
                          <m:mi>m</m:mi>
                          <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                        </m:msub>
